iels</i>, a shortened form of <i>Nikolaus</i> (see   Nicholas  ). Compare   Nielson  ,   Neilsen  ,   Nelsen  ,   Nilsen  , and   Nilson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Neilsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Ejnar, Gurli, Jorgen, Nels, Niels.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Nielsen  . Compare   Neilson   3.","Scottish (Midlothian): variant of   Neilson   1."]},{"name":"Nelsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Nels, Erik, Einer, Berger, Folmer, Holger, Iver, Juel, Morten, Thor, Uffe.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Nielsen   or   Nilsen  . Compare   Nelson  .","Flemish and German: patronymic from   Nelis  ."]}]},{"name":"Andreas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The original New Testament Greek form of   Andrew  , used in the English-speaking world as a learned variant."],"variants":[{"name":"Andries","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353273,"age":99,"year":"1350","julianDay":2214138,"description":"Plague ravishes Denmark and Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Andreas Nielsen was born in Denmark as the son of Niels Aleksandersen and Ukendt. He married Ukendt before 1270, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","–1270":"–1270","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1255":"1255","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","before 1270":"enne 1270","1270":"1270","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Europe":"Europe","Denmark":"Taani"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","–1270":"–1270","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","about 1270":"noin 1270","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1255":"1255","about 1310":"noin 1310","1350":"13